151
00:16:15.811 --> 00:16:22.953
<v Maya>brain creates a powerful shortcut. It says, this thing is communicating with me, therefore it is a subject, not an object.</v>

152
00:16:23.433 --> 00:16:30.555
<v Daniel>So if the AI is useful to me, or if it just feels like it's genuinely listening, my brain just forgives the fact that its ears aren't moving quite right.</v>

153
00:16:30.850 --> 00:16:37.756
<v Maya>You don't just forgive it. On a neurological level, you literally stop seeing it. The experts in the study call this emotional flooding.</v>

154
00:16:37.916 --> 00:16:38.676
<v Daniel>Emotional flooding.</v>

155
00:16:38.797 --> 00:16:46.883
<v Maya>The emotional connection you feel during the interaction floods the uncanny valley. You stop judging the geometry of the face and you start trying to figure out what the agent is thinking.</v>

156
00:16:47.244 --> 00:16:54.970
<v Daniel>This connects right back to that AI trust curve we mentioned. The curve goes from fear and the ick, but then it shoots way up to a phase of high trust.</v>

157
00:16:55.325 --> 00:17:08.371
<v Maya>Yes, and that is where it gets, well, dangerous, or at least very complicated. Because once your brain crosses that interaction bridge, you often overshoot. The source specifically mentions the movie Her.</v>

158
00:17:08.611 --> 00:17:11.652
<v Daniel>Right, with Joaquin Phoenix falling in love with his operating system.</v>

159
00:17:11.903 --> 00:17:26.427
<v Maya>That's the extreme sci-fi version. But we see little versions of it all the time already. People saying please and thank you to ChatGPT. I do that. We all do. People confessing their deepest secrets to therapeutic chatbots.</v>

160
00:17:27.127 --> 00:17:34.169
<v Maya>Once that interaction loop is closed, we can't help but project humanity onto the machine. Our brains are wired to fill in the blanks.</v>

161
00:17:34.489 --> 00:17:39.991
<v Daniel>So the solution to the uncanny valley isn't necessarily perfect biology. It's perfect psychology.</v>

162
00:17:40.232 --> 00:17:43.916
<v Maya>In a way, yes. If you can convince the mind, the eye relaxes its standards.</v>

163
00:17:44.016 --> 00:17:53.285
<v Daniel>But, and this is a really big but, for that interaction to feel real and not just like a script, the agent can't just be a pretty puppet. It has to actually be smart. It has to understand the world.</v>

164
00:17:53.365 --> 00:17:54.306
<v Maya>It has to have a brain.</v>

165
00:17:54.726 --> 00:17:58.010
<v Daniel>Which brings us to section three of our sources, world models.</v>

166
00:17:58.586 --> 00:18:04.748
<v Maya>This is the real meat of that huge meta research paper. This is the brain behind the face.</v>

167
00:18:05.088 --> 00:18:12.490
<v Daniel>I feel like world model is a buzzword we hear thrown around a lot. So let's actually define it. What is a world model in the context of AI?</v>

168
00:18:12.751 --> 00:18:26.775
<v Maya>A world model is an internal representation of how reality functions. It's what allows an agent to reason, to predict what will happen next, and to plan its actions. It's the fundamental difference between a reflex and a thought.</v>

169
00:18:27.162 --> 00:18:30.063
<v Daniel>Okay, give me the explain like I'm five version of that.</v>

170
00:18:30.103 --> 00:18:34.623
<v Maya>All right. Imagine you're planning a road trip, let's say from New York to Los Angeles.</v>

171
00:18:34.643 --> 00:18:35.244
<v Daniel>Okay, I'm with you.</v>

172
00:18:35.684 --> 00:18:50.146
<v Maya>In your head, you are visualizing that trip. You see the map of the country. You think about where you'll need to stop for gas. You anticipate traffic around Chicago. But are you visualizing every single leaf on every single tree along the entire</v>

173
00:18:50.206 --> 00:18:51.087
<v Maya>highway? God,</v>

174
00:18:51.147 --> 00:18:51.347
no.

175
00:18:51.487 --> 00:18:53.267
<v Daniel>That would be impossible. My brain would melt.</v>

176
00:18:53.487 --> 00:18:57.777
<v Maya>Are you visualizing the exact texture of the asphalt for every single mile of I-80?</v>

177
00:18:57.937 --> 00:19:01.325
<v Daniel>No. I'm visualizing the route, the concept of the trip.</v>

178
00:19:01.627 --> 00:19:16.618
<v Maya>Exactly. You are using an abstract model of the world. You strip away all the irrelevant sensory noise and you focus only on the signals that matter for your plan. Okay. Now compare that to how we currently do a lot of generative AI, like those AI video generators</v>

179
00:19:16.678 --> 00:19:17.479
<v Maya>we see online.</v>

180
00:19:17.519 --> 00:19:20.721
<v Daniel>The ones that make those weird morphing wobbly videos.</v>

181
00:19:20.821 --> 00:19:35.429
<v Maya>Right. Those models are working in what's called pixel space. If you ask one for a video of a road trip, it is obsessively trying to predict the color of every single pixel in the next frame. Is pixel number 4732 going</v>

182
00:19:36.189 --> 00:19:37.470
<v Maya>to be green or gray?</v>

183
00:19:37.650 --> 00:19:39.250
<v Daniel>It doesn't actually know what a car is.</v>

184
00:19:39.471 --> 00:19:45.833
<v Maya>Not at all. It just knows that a certain cluster of gray pixels usually hangs out near a certain cluster of black pixels.</v>

185
00:19:45.873 --> 00:19:52.516
<v Daniel>That's why you see those videos where a dog suddenly grows a fifth leg or a car just kind of melts into a bicycle halfway down the street.</v>

186
00:19:52.597 --> 00:19:53.457
<v Maya>It's hallucinating.</v>

187
00:19:53.677 --> 00:19:58.699
<v Daniel>The AI is hallucinating because it's just painting by numbers. It's not understanding the actual object.</v>

188
00:19:59.159 --> 00:20:13.803
<v Maya>Precisely. It has no sense of object permanence. It has no concept of physics. It's basically a dream machine. And Meta is arguing that this whole approach is a complete dead end for embodied AI. If a robot is holding a glass of water, it can't be</v>

189
00:20:13.923 --> 00:20:20.065
<v Maya>dreaming about the glass. It needs to know with certainty that if it lets go, gravity is going to happen.</v>

190
00:20:20.245 --> 00:20:23.186
<v Daniel>So what's the alternative? The paper talks about something called JEPA.</v>

191
00:20:23.406 --> 00:20:26.227
<v Maya>Right. Joint embedding predictive architecture.</v>

192
00:20:26.327 --> 00:20:27.048
<v Daniel>And swan tights.</v>

193
00:20:27.128 --> 00:20:38.633
<v Maya>I know. It's a mouthful. But the concept behind it is actually really beautiful and intuitive. Instead of predicting the next pixel, Jaypa learns to predict the next state of the world in an abstract space.</v>

194
00:20:38.813 --> 00:20:40.614
<v Daniel>Okay. Use the dog analogy again for me.</v>

195
00:20:40.674 --> 00:20:55.524
<v Maya>All right. Imagine you throw a frisbee for a dog. A pixel generator is trying to guess the color of the grass in the sky in the very next frame. Jaypa is different. Jaypa is saying concept, dog, action, jump, physics. Gravity. It then predicts at a high</v>

196
00:20:55.564 --> 00:20:57.307
<v Maya>level the dog must come down.</v>

197
00:20:57.608 --> 00:20:59.671
<v Daniel>It doesn't care if the grass is light green or dark green.</v>

198
00:21:00.072 --> 00:21:09.396
<v Maya>It doesn't care about the pixels. It cares that the event obeys the known laws of reality. It's predicting the representation, not the raw sensory data.</v>

199
00:21:09.636 --> 00:21:12.718
<v Daniel>It's simulating the logic of the world, not just the image of the world.</v>

200
00:21:12.778 --> 00:21:25.766
<v Maya>Yes. And that is absolutely essential for anything that has to move and interact. If you're a robot, you need to know that a wall is solid. You don't need to know the exact texture of the wallpaper to understand that you can't walk through it.</v>

201
00:21:26.469 --> 00:21:37.454
<v Daniel>So that's the physical world model. It's for dealing with gravity and walls and solid objects. But the paper also talks about a mental world model. And this, to me, felt even more sci-fi.</v>

202
00:21:37.594 --> 00:21:52.280
<v Maya>This is where we get into theory of mind. For an agent to be truly useful and collaborative, especially a wearable agent that literally lives on your face, it needs to be able to model your brain. It needs to understand that you have beliefs and, crucially, that those</v>

203
00:21:52.300 --> 00:21:53.220
<v Maya>beliefs might be wrong.</v>

204
00:21:53.415 --> 00:21:55.897
<v Daniel>The classic Sally Ann test from developmental psychology.</v>

205
00:21:55.917 --> 00:21:59.901
<v Maya>The very same. Let's play it out really quick. I'm an evil robot. You are. Let's call you Beth. I</v>

206
00:21:59.941 --> 00:22:00.781
<v Daniel>am Beth. Sounds</v>

207
00:22:00.801 --> 00:22:05.505
<v Maya>good. You put your phone down on the desk in front of you and then you walk out of the room to get a coffee.</v>

208
00:22:05.586 --> 00:22:07.367
<v Daniel>Okay, I'm gone. I'm getting a latte.</v>

209
00:22:07.427 --> 00:22:12.812
<v Maya>While you're gone, I, the evil robot, take your phone and I hide it in the refrigerator.</v>

210
00:22:13.332 --> 00:22:13.893
<v Daniel>You jerk.</v>

211
00:22:14.713 --> 00:22:21.577
<v Maya>I am a chaotic agent. Now, you walk back into the room. You want to check your phone. Where is the first place you look?</v>

212
00:22:21.777 --> 00:22:24.158
<v Daniel>I look on the desk because that's where I left it.</v>

213
00:22:24.278 --> 00:22:38.565
<v Maya>Correct. You have what's called a false belief. Your mental model of the world is out of sync with reality. But a dumb AI, a current generation AI, if you ask it, where will Beth look for her phone?</v>

214
00:22:39.365 --> 00:22:40.706
<v Maya>It will say the fridge.</v>

215
00:22:41.245 --> 00:22:44.528
<v Daniel>Because the AI knows the phone is in the fridge, it has the ground truth.</v>

216
00:22:44.688 --> 00:22:51.834
<v Maya>Exactly. It assumes that because it knows the truth, you must also know the truth. It can't distinguish between objective reality and your subjective belief.</v>

217
00:22:52.034 --> 00:22:58.059
<v Daniel>And why does this matter for a real product? I mean, why does my smart assistant need to know that I might be delusional?</v>

218
00:22:58.499 --> 00:23:12.738
<v Maya>It's all about interpreting your intent. Imagine you're leaving your house. You're wearing those meta-ray bands. The AI, through the camera, sees your keys sitting on the kitchen counter. You walk out the front door. Should the AI yell at you?</v>

219
00:23:13.219 --> 00:23:15.842
<v Daniel>Well, if I forgot my keys, then yes, absolutely it should.</v>

220
00:23:15.862 --> 00:23:19.947
<v Maya>What if you left them there on purpose? What if you're just walking out to the mailbox and you'll be right back?</v>

221
00:23:20.307 --> 00:23:22.530
<v Daniel>Then I'd be incredibly annoyed if it started yelling at me.</v>

222
00:23:22.690 --> 00:23:37.190
<v Maya>Exactly. The AI has to look at your behavior and model your internal mental state. Did he see the keys and consciously ignore them? Or did he never even look in the direction of the keys? The difference between user is forgetting and user is</v>

223
00:23:37.230 --> 00:23:41.734
<v Maya>deciding is entirely internal to you. It's a theory of mind problem.</v>

224
00:23:41.934 --> 00:23:47.559
<v Daniel>If it gets that wrong, it goes from being Jargus, your helpful assistant, to being a nagging spouse.</v>

225
00:23:47.980 --> 00:23:50.802
<v Maya>And nobody is going to pay for the nagging spouse upgrade.</v>

226
00:23:51.448 --> 00:24:03.353
<v Daniel>So, okay, we've built the perfect face, or at least we're trying to. We've built the brain, both physical and mental world models. Now we need to actually talk about the body itself. And that brings us to section four, the hardware.</v>

227
00:24:03.634 --> 00:24:12.998
<v Maya>We're moving from the purely digital to the physical. And the meta paper really splits this into two categories, wearable agents and robotic agents.</v>

228
00:24:13.478 --> 00:24:18.840
<v Daniel>Let's start with wearables. This is basically the her scenario, but with cameras attached.</v>

229
00:24:19.060 --> 00:24:22.802
<v Maya>The key technical term here is egocentric perception.</v>

230
00:24:23.242 --> 00:24:25.563
<v Daniel>Which sounds a bit like a narcissist robot.</v>

231
00:24:25.823 --> 00:24:33.446
<v Maya>It does sound bad, but it just means first person view. The AI sees the world from your center. It shares your perceptual field.</v>

232
00:24:33.866 --> 00:24:35.747
<v Daniel>So this is for tasks like show and tell.</v>

233
00:24:36.127 --> 00:24:42.590
<v Maya>Right. Hey Meta, look at this weird vegetable I found at the farmer's market. What is it? Or, hey Meta, can you see where I put my wallet?</v>

234
00:24:42.978 --> 00:24:51.445
<v Daniel>It sounds incredibly useful. I mean, I lose my wallet on a daily basis. But the paper suggests that these agents are actually, well, kind of bad at this right now.</v>

235
00:24:51.485 --> 00:24:58.451
<v Maya>They are struggling. There's a specific benchmark they use called world prediction. And the stats that came out of it are really quite humbling for the field.</v>

236
00:24:58.831 --> 00:24:59.792
<v Daniel>OK, hit me with the numbers.</v>

237
00:25:00.213 --> 00:25:12.699
<v Maya>So humans, as you can imagine, are incredibly good at predicting the next logical step in a procedure. If I'm watching you chop an onion, get a pan out and then grab a bottle of olive oil. I have a very good idea of what you're about to do.</v>

238
00:25:12.779 --> 00:25:14.120
<v Daniel>You know I'm going to sauté those onions.</v>

239
00:25:14.160 --> 00:25:26.911
<v Maya>You're sautéing. Humans have near 100% accuracy on predicting that next immediate step. The state-of-the-art AI models that they tested, they hover at around 57% accuracy.</v>

240
00:25:26.952 --> 00:25:30.635
<v Daniel>57%. Yeah. That's barely better than a coin flip.</v>

241
00:25:30.795 --> 00:25:32.577
<v Maya>It's barely better than random guessing.</v>

242
00:25:33.117 --> 00:25:39.754
<v Daniel>But why? If these models have read every single recipe on the entire internet, why can't they figure out I'm making pasta?</v>

243
00:25:39.934 --> 00:25:51.596
<v Maya>Because they struggle profoundly with something called action equivalence. They don't have the common sense to understand that there are often multiple equally valid ways to skin a cat or multiple ways to make an omelet.</v>

244
00:25:51.856 --> 00:25:52.596
<v Daniel>A rigidity problem.</v>

245
00:25:52.656 --> 00:26:05.256
<v Maya>A huge rigidity problem. If the AI was trained on a million videos where the chef salts the pasta water before it starts boiling and you happen to salt it after it boils... The AI gets completely confused.</v>

246
00:26:05.376 --> 00:26:06.497
<v Daniel>It thinks I've gone off script.</v>

247
00:26:06.857 --> 00:26:17.642
<v Maya>It thinks you're failing the task. It doesn't understand the goal, which is just to have salty water. It only understands the specific sequence of pixels that it memorized from its training data.</v>

248
00:26:17.903 --> 00:26:24.331
<v Daniel>So there's a difference between a real chef and someone who is just blindly following a recipe card without any understanding.</v>

249
00:26:24.411 --> 00:26:37.107
<v Maya>And that fragility makes them intensely frustrating to use in the real world. If you grab the blue knife instead of the red knife from the knife block, the AI might panic and give you a wrong instruction because the training video happened to use a red knife.</v>

250
00:26:37.442 --> 00:26:44.844
<v Daniel>So that's wearables. But at least wearables only have to watch me mess up in the kitchen. Robotic agents have to actually do the work. They have to touch things.</v>

251
00:26:45.044 --> 00:26:49.846
<v Maya>The touch barrier. This is in many ways the final boss of embodied AI.</v>

252
00:26:49.946 --> 00:26:58.348
<v Daniel>We see all these videos of robots from like Boston Dynamics doing backflips and parkour. It looks incredibly impressive. So why can't they fold my laundry?</v>

253
00:26:58.603 --> 00:27:06.392
<v Maya>Because, and this sounds completely counterintuitive, backflips are actually mathematically much, much easier than folding laundry.</v>

254
00:27:06.412 --> 00:27:07.433
<v Daniel>Okay, you have to explain that.</v>

255
00:27:07.873 --> 00:27:22.799
<v Maya>A backflip is what's called rigid body physics. It's just mass, velocity, momentum. The robot is a solid, predictable object. The floor is a solid, predictable object. It's pure, calculable math. Laundry, on the other</v>

256
00:27:22.839 --> 00:27:36.147
<v Maya>hand, laundry is a deformable object. A sock has no set shape. It can be a ball. It can be a long strip. It can be a crumpled pile. It changes shape the moment you touch it. It has static clang. It has friction that changes based on the material. It's</v>

257
00:27:36.207 --> 00:27:36.848
<v Daniel>pure chaos. It</v>

258
00:27:36.888 --> 00:27:42.770
<v Maya>is physical chaos. And this brings us to the biggest problem in robotics, which is the sim to real gap.</v>

259
00:27:42.890 --> 00:27:44.131
<v Daniel>Simulation to reality.</v>

260
00:27:44.251 --> 00:27:52.855
<v Maya>Right. We train robots in virtual simulations because it's faster and cheaper. We can run a million hours of virtual laundry folding in a single day on a server farm.</v>

261
00:27:53.190 --> 00:27:55.771
<v Daniel>But the virtual sock doesn't act exactly like a real sock.</v>

262
00:27:55.852 --> 00:28:10.840
<v Maya>Not even close. In the simulation, the physics are perfect and simplified. There's no dust in the air. There's no grease or moisture on the robot's fingers. There's no random air draft from the HVAC system. So when you take that perfectly trained brain and you put it in a real robot</v>

263
00:28:11.080 --> 00:28:13.962
<v Maya>in your real messy house, it fails.</v>

264
00:28:14.142 --> 00:28:14.722
<v Daniel>How does it fail?</v>

265
00:28:14.882 --> 00:28:25.805
<v Maya>The robot reaches for the sock, but maybe the sock is silkier than the one in the simulation, so it slips just a millimeter. The robot's sensors can't handle that. It freezes. It has no tactile intuition.</v>

266
00:28:26.125 --> 00:28:33.769
<v Daniel>Humans have fingertips with thousands of nerve endings. We feel that slip, and we instantly, subconsciously adjust our grip.</v>

267
00:28:33.869 --> 00:28:48.718
<v Maya>We don't even have to think about it. We dynamically adjust our grip pressure dozens of times a second. Current robots are almost entirely visual. They're trying to see if they're holding the object correctly. Imagine trying to tie your shoes with your hands completely numb only by</v>

268
00:28:48.778 --> 00:28:49.258
<v Maya>watching them.</v>

269
00:28:49.593 --> 00:28:51.793
<v Daniel>That would be a complete nightmare. I couldn't do it.</v>

270
00:28:51.913 --> 00:28:54.994
<v Maya>That is the state of mainstream robotics right now. They are numb.</v>

271
00:28:55.394 --> 00:29:10.377
<v Daniel>So how do we fix this? How do we get from this numb robot to the useful butler that we've been promised for decades? This leads us to the final section, section five, future directions. The researchers propose a new way</v>

272
00:29:10.437 --> 00:29:10.877
<v Daniel>of learning.</v>

273
00:29:11.077 --> 00:29:13.817
<v Maya>They call it the unification of system A and system B.</v>

274
00:29:14.077 --> 00:29:17.118
<v Daniel>This sounds a lot like Daniel Kahneman's thinking fast and slow.</v>

275
00:29:17.501 --> 00:29:25.323
<v Maya>It's a very similar concept. So system A is learning by observation. This is passive. This is the AI watching YouTube videos.</v>

276
00:29:25.383 --> 00:29:31.004
<v Daniel>Right. I watch a five minute video of a guy fixing a leaky sink and suddenly I feel like I'm a master plumber.</v>

277
00:29:31.124 --> 00:29:45.148
<v Maya>Exactly. You get the general idea. You see the pattern. And AI is very, very good at this. It can watch a billion hours of video, but it has no grounding. You don't actually know how tight the bolt should be or what it feels like when the threads catch.</v>

278
00:29:45.435 --> 00:29:46.315
<v Daniel>And system B is?</v>

279
00:29:46.596 --> 00:29:57.241
<v Maya>System B is learning by action. This is trial and error. This is you actually picking up the wrench. You turn it. It slips off the bolt. You bust your knuckles. You try again with a different amount of force.</v>

280
00:29:57.341 --> 00:29:58.622
<v Daniel>This is reinforcement learning.</v>

281
00:29:58.682 --> 00:30:11.508
<v Maya>Yes. It's the only way to get true physical grounding. But it's incredibly slow. The technical term is sample inefficient. You have to fail 10,000 times just to learn one specific simple movement.</v>

282
00:30:11.835 --> 00:30:19.782
<v Daniel>So we have one system that is very fast but shallow, which is watching, and another system that is very deep but agonizingly slow, which is doing.</v>

283
00:30:20.302 --> 00:30:26.788
<v Maya>And the grand challenge, the holy grail, is to merge them. The analogy they use throughout the paper is babies.</v>

284
00:30:26.928 --> 00:30:29.290
<v Daniel>Babies are the ultimate learning machines, for sure.</v>

285
00:30:29.534 --> 00:30:37.656
<v Maya>Think about a baby in a high chair. They watch their parents eating. That's system A. They're passively absorbing the patterns of movement. But then what do they do?</v>

286
00:30:37.676 --> 00:30:38.937
<v Daniel>They start smashing things.</v>

287
00:30:38.977 --> 00:30:50.240
<v Maya>They motor babble. They smash the peas on the tray. They drop the spoon on the floor over and over again. They put the toy in their mouth to see what it feels like.</v>

288
00:30:50.340 --> 00:30:51.580
<v Daniel>We move in order to see.</v>

289
00:30:52.133 --> 00:31:06.260
<v Maya>That's the core philosophy from the paper. The baby is using interaction, using system B to generate new data. Oh, when I drop the spoon, it makes a loud noise and mom makes a funny face. That new data then trains their internal world model, their system A.</v>

290
00:31:06.540 --> 00:31:15.205
<v Daniel>So Meta wants to build AI that learns like a baby. It watches, but then it actively pokes and prods the world to verify and refine its understanding.</v>

291
00:31:15.325 --> 00:31:17.927
<v Maya>Exactly. Move, see, update the model, repeat.</v>

292
00:31:18.167 --> 00:31:32.875
<v Daniel>That's fascinating. But it also hints at this future where our homes are just filled with these things, all learning, all watching, all interacting with each other. The paper briefly touches on multi-agent collaboration.</v>

293
00:31:33.503 --> 00:31:47.127
<v Maya>And this is the really messy, complicated future. You won't just have the AI in your house. You're going to have a whole fleet of specialized agents. Your glasses are an agent. Your refrigerator is an agent. Your car is an agent.</v>

294
00:31:47.207 --> 00:31:49.347
<v Daniel>And they could all have different goals and different information?</v>

295
00:31:49.607 --> 00:32:01.231
<v Maya>Correct. And that creates a massive conflict resolution problem that hasn't been solved yet. Imagine your smart fridge agent knows you're on a diet. It sees you reaching for the cake. It locks the door. No cake for you.</v>

296
00:32:01.251 --> 00:32:02.731
<v Daniel>That's a good fridge. I need that fridge.</v>

297
00:32:03.312 --> 00:32:12.557
<v Maya>But at the same time, your smartwatch agent knows you just ran 10 miles and your blood sugar is getting dangerously low. It sends a message to the other agents, give them the cake immediately.</v>

298
00:32:12.837 --> 00:32:16.759
<v Daniel>So now my kitchen appliances are arguing with each other about my caloric intake.</v>

299
00:32:17.180 --> 00:32:32.088
<v Maya>Who wins that argument? Does the health and safety protocol from the watch outrank the dietary plan protocol from the fridge? Do they vote on it? This sounds like a funny far-off problem, but it's a legitimate technical protocol that simply hasn't been written yet.</v>

300
00:32:33.268 --> 00:32:38.374
<v Maya>How do these different world models synchronize when they have conflicting data and conflicting goals about the user?</v>

301
00:32:38.795 --> 00:32:47.165
<v Daniel>It sounds just like my own internal monologue. You know, my brain versus my stomach. Now we're just externalizing that fight into our kitchen appliances.</v>

