314
00:34:12.396 --> 00:34:13.578
<v Daniel>We start to treat them like people.</v>

315
00:34:13.973 --> 00:34:28.543
<v Maya>And that's dangerous because the illusion will eventually break. The trust curve gives a stark warning about this. When the illusion shatters, when your trusted AI friend suddenly hallucinates or gets a software update that changes its personality or just</v>

316
00:34:28.643 --> 00:34:32.825
<v Maya>glitches out, we don't just feel annoyed like we do when an app crashes.</v>

317
00:34:32.845 --> 00:34:33.586
<v Daniel>We feel betrayed.</v>

318
00:34:33.846 --> 00:34:48.600
<v Maya>We feel betrayed. It's not a software bug. It's a violation of a social contract that we thought we had. If you treat your AI like a therapist and then it suddenly uses your confessions to show you an ad for antidepressants, that psychological damage is real and</v>

319
00:34:48.660 --> 00:34:53.845
<v Maya>profound. We are deeply vulnerable to things that convincingly mimic humanity.</v>

320
00:34:54.501 --> 00:35:04.684
<v Daniel>So where does this leave us? I mean, we've covered the horror of the death mask, the incredible complexity of the world model, the clumsiness of modern robots, and the profound risk of betrayal. It's a lot to take in.</v>

321
00:35:04.984 --> 00:35:19.849
<v Maya>It is. But I want to go back to that AI Trust Curve article for a final thought. It had a really interesting take on the ick that we feel. We're currently trapped in this cycle of hype and repulsion. One week, we think AI is a god that's going to solve all our problems. The next week, we</v>

322
00:35:19.889 --> 00:35:33.972
<v Maya>see a weird animation and think it's a zombie that's going to destroy us. But the article suggests we need to recalibrate our entire relationship with it. We need to stop treating AI like a magic wizard and also stop treating it like a monster.</v>

323
00:35:34.112 --> 00:35:35.172
<v Daniel>So what should we treat it like?</v>

324
00:35:35.392 --> 00:35:35.872
<v Maya>A mirror.</v>

325
00:35:36.152 --> 00:35:36.593
<v Daniel>A mirror.</v>

326
00:35:36.833 --> 00:35:51.756
<v Maya>Think about it. Garbage in, garbage out. The AI is trained on human data. It's a vast statistical reflection of us. If a chat bot is biased, it's because our society is biased. If an avatar is uncanny, it's because we haven't yet figured out how to fully model our own</v>

327
00:35:51.796 --> 00:36:02.519
<v Maya>biology. That feeling of ick. That repulsion we feel when we look into the uncanny valley. It might just be the deep discomfort of seeing a reflection that is almost us but has been stripped of its soul.</v>

328
00:36:02.679 --> 00:36:04.120
<v Daniel>That is a heavy thought to end on.</v>

329
00:36:04.340 --> 00:36:16.324
<v Maya>It is. But I also think it's kind of empowering. It means the future of AI isn't something that's just happening to us. It's something we are actively building for better or for worse. The mirror can only reflect what we choose to put in front of it.</v>

330
00:36:16.595 --> 00:36:31.415
<v Daniel>So here's our challenge to you, the listener. For the next week, try to observe your own trust curve. When you're talking to Siri or you see a digital influencer on Instagram or you're using ChatGPT for work, just catch yourself. Are you trusting it too much? Are you</v>

331
00:36:31.435 --> 00:36:36.422
<v Daniel>getting the ick? And then ask yourself, what is that machine reflecting back at you?</v>

